-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Show that √1 000 000 − ³√1 000 000 equals 900. 2. [Key Idea] Express 1 000 000 as a power of 10 (10⁶); then square- and cube-roots become simple exponents whose difference is immediate. 3. [Proof] Let N = 1 000 000 = 10⁶. √N = (10⁶)^{1/2} = 10^{6·(1/2)} = 10³ = 1000. ³√N = (10⁶)^{1/3} = 10^{6·(1/3)} = 10² = 100. Therefore √1 000 000 − ³√1 000 000 = 1000 − 100 = 900. Alternative (prime-factor) style: 1 000 000 = 2⁶ · 5⁶. √(2⁶ · 5⁶) = 2³ · 5³ = 8 · 125 = 1000, ³√(2⁶ · 5⁶) = 2² · 5² = 4 · 25 = 100. Difference = 1000 − 100 = 900. 4. [Conclusion] The required value is 900.
